library(readr)
db <- read_csv("diabetes.csv")
Parsed with column specification:
cols(
  Pregnancies = col_integer(),

  BloodPressure = col_integer(),
  SkinThickness = col_integer(),

#Before I commit to any further I will change the Outcome column to Positive and Negative for the sake of data visualization
# <0> Being negative
# <1> Being positive
db$Outcome <- factor(db$Outcome, levels = c("0", "1"), labels = c("negative", "positive"))
#This will create an aditional column in our data set that will transform the column of pregancies, I will make a distinction between the cases where people have from 0 to 5 pregnancies and people who has between 6 and 18
db$PregnanciesCut<-cut(db$Pregnancies, breaks = c(0,6,18),labels = c("0-5 pregnancies","6-18 pregnancies"),right = FALSE)
db$Pregnancies<-as.factor(db$Pregnancies)
#This will create an aditional column in our data set that will transform the column of glucose, I tried to split the data into equal halves and I will make distinction between the people who has Plasma Glucose of 0 to 120 and 120 to 200
summary(db$Glucose)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
    0.0    99.0   117.0   120.9   140.2   199.0 
db$GlucoseCut<-cut(db$Glucose, breaks = c(0,120,200),labels = c("0-120 Glucose","120-200 Glucose"),right = FALSE)
db$Glucose<-as.factor(db$Glucose)
#This will create an aditional column in our data set that will transform the column of blood pressure between the people who has a blood pressure between 0 and 68 and the people who ahs a blood pressure of 69 to 123

   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.

db$BloodPressure<-as.factor(db$BloodPressure)
#This will create an aditional column in our data set that will transform the column of Skin Thickness, the values will be divided between people with a skin thickness of 0 to 25 adn those between 26 and 100
db$SkinThicknessCut<-cut(db$SkinThickness, breaks = c(0,25,100),labels = c("0-25 SkinT","25-100 SkinT"),right = FALSE)
db$SkinThickness<-as.factor(db$SkinThickness)

#well that's quite a bit the number of outliers for all the columns, nonetheless I wil perform an exhaustive outlier detection where I will be using PCA for outliers detection, z-score, and cooks distance.
#On another note I must mention that I know why the skewness and the outliers are quite noticeable, as it is stated in the UCI repository webpage there are some values for certain columns that biologically they can't be 0, so they must be treated as outliers, because of that the skewness might seem off, and the plots might be reporting more outleirs that there actually, but that is something I will deal with in depth in the next Stage - DATA PREPARATION

STAGE THREE - DATA PREPARATION

###MISSING VALUES AND OUTLIERS###
library(readr)
db <- read.csv("diabetes.csv")
#As it is stated in the UCI Machine Learning Repository there are missing values in the current data set
#Although they are not marked with NA but instead with 0, and for some of the columns that is a biological impossibility
#We will start to see which columns have 0 and of those which ones can actually have values of 0
#Pregnancies Column
# Number of times pregnant 
nrow(db[db$Pregnancies %in% 0 ,])
[1] 111
#Of course you can live perfectly without being pregnant so these zeroes are not missing values
#Glucose Column
#Plasma glucose concentration a 2 hours in an oral glucose tolerance test 
nrow(db[db$Glucose %in% 0 ,])
[1] 5
#We have five rows with levels of 0, and while that is possible (see link below) they might end up being outliers, so for the 
#time being this fives zeroes will be treated as missing values
# https://depts.washington.edu/uwcoe/healthtopics/diabetes.html
#Blood Pressure
#Diastolic blood pressure (mm Hg) 
nrow(db[db$BloodPressure %in% 0 ,])
[1] 35
#This is interesting, apparently you can have a DBP of 0 in cases of severe hypotension, stiff arteries in elderly, arteriovenous #malformation, aortic dissection and guess what? due to diabetes too. Since these cases themselves can be considered outliers
# and sometimes the equipment can fail to I will consider these zeroes as missing values.
# https://www.researchgate.net/publication/304033901_Zero_diastolic_blood_pressure
#Skin thickness
#Triceps skin fold thickness (mm) 
nrow(db[db$SkinThickness %in% 0 ,])
[1] 227
#This is indeed a biological impossibility so all those 227 zeroes will be considered as missing values (which is a lot of missing data)
#Insulin Column
#2-Hour serum insulin (mu U/ml) 
nrow(db[db$Insulin %in% 0 ,])
[1] 374
#This is also impossible so all those 374 values will be treated as missing values
#BMI
#Body mass index (weight in kg/(height in m)^2) 
nrow(db[db$BMI %in% 0 ,])
[1] 11
# This (weight in kg/(height in m)^2) explains itself in that it is impossible a value of 0
#Diabetes pedigree function
nrow(db[db$DiabetesPedigreeFunction %in% 0 ,])
[1] 0
#Age
nrow(db[db$Age %in% 0 ,])
[1] 0
#Now we have seen there are quite a bit of missing data, and imputing it will prove quite the challenge.
#I will explore different methods and I will stick to what I believe works the best given each particular case
#For now I will convert all those zeroes in the column that don't allow zeroes into NA character
db$Glucose[db$Glucose == 0] <- NA
db$BloodPressure[db$BloodPressure == 0] <- NA
db$SkinThickness[db$SkinThickness == 0] <- NA
db$Insulin[db$Insulin == 0] <- NA
db$BMI[db$BMI == 0] <- NA
#Now as recommendation by Dr.Martin I will explore the data for potential outliers and see if they need to be removed and how and why or not
#I will begin looking for outlier first with the most basic method, by those values who are 3 standard deviations away from tehir z-score
#Outliers for the Pregnancies column
z<-(mean(db$Pregnancies)-db$Pregnancies)/sd(db$Pregnancies)
z<-abs(z)
outliers1<-z[which(z>3)]
outliers1
[1] 3.310488 3.904034 3.013715 3.013715
outliers2<-which(z>3)
outliers2
[1]  89 160 299 456
db$Pregnancies[outliers2]
[1] 15 17 14 14
dbop<-subset.data.frame(db, z>3)
dbop
#So far we have four expected values, we won't deal with them just yet until further analysis has #been done
#Outliers for the Glucose column
z<-(mean(db$Glucose)-db$Glucose)/sd(db$Glucose)
z<-abs(z)
outliers1<-z[which(z>3)]
outliers1
numeric(0)
outliers2<-which(z>3)
outliers2
integer(0)
db$Glucose[outliers2]
integer(0)
dbog<-subset.data.frame(db, z>3)
dbog
#Good news for the glucose column it seems like it doesn't have outliers
#Outliers for the Blood Pressure column
z<-(mean(db$BloodPressure)-db$BloodPressure)/sd(db$BloodPressure)
z<-abs(z)
outliers1<-z[which(z>3)]
outliers1
numeric(0)
outliers2<-which(z>3)

#Unfortunately Cooks distance doesn't help much as it show and extraordinary amount of outliers, but what is interesting nonetheless is that for the last plot generated by cooks distance there's only two outliers present, as well as cooks distance as proven useful sometimes this time seems that indeed  further analysis will be required. #The next method to detect these outliers is PCA Analysis and it will be implemented in two #different ways. The firt will be plotting the Principal Component and the second one will be
#based on the IQR
#First method
dbpca<- cbind.data.frame(db$Pregnancies,db$DiabetesPedigreeFunction,db$Age)

#Second Method
library(qqplotr)
library(ggplot2)
library(graphics)
library(caret)
pca <- prcomp(dbpca) 
identify(qqnorm(pca$x[,2],pch = 20, col = c(rep("red", 33), rep("blue", 99))))
integer(0)

pr <- prcomp(dbpca,center = TRUE, scale. = TRUE)
transformedData <- predict(preProcess(dbpca,method = c("center","scale")),dbpca)
mu <- colMeans(transformedData)
distFromMu <- sweep(transformedData,2,mu,'-')
distFromMu <- abs(distFromMu)
lam <- apply(pr$x,2,var)
nominator <- (as.matrix(distFromMu)%*%as.matrix(pr$rotation))**2
Res <- sweep(nominator,2,lam,'/')
scores <- rowSums(Res)
maxScore = which.max(scores)
dbpca[maxScore,]
head(scores)
[1]  2.2263850  0.9871394  2.4495400  2.0173505 32.9245077  0.8085754
tail(scores)
[1] 4.5089314 7.4268336 0.5369123 0.6067650 1.5509101 1.1766062
is_outlier <- function(x) {
  return(x < quantile(x, 0.25) - 3 * IQR(x) | x > quantile(x, 0.75) + 3 * IQR(x))
}
outpca<-is_outlier(scores)

#Now this method leaves with a rather complex situation

#Conclusion:
#AS I've seen before outlier treatment is not an easy task, and much of it comes down to my own criteria and jugdment. Another issue it need to be taken into account with the current data it that as less data as we eliminate the better because of the size of the data set.
#I think in this case, as I've done before, the best solution in this case is to eliminate the extreme outliers, which I think in this casse would be the row 446, 229, 5, 460 and 371
#In any case, this is not permament so it can be reverted or modified at any time if I do deem it necessary
db1<-db[-c(446, 229, 5,460,371), ]
####Missing Values treatment
#As we stated above there are a few columns that do not allow to have 0 as their values, and those columns are Blood Pressure. skin thickness, insulin, and BMI (Body Mass Index), and the glucose column which is a special case.
#My objective is to treat up those columns that have fewer number of missing values than the others. As we have seen above there some columns that have 35 missing values while others have 227. My idea is that cleaning up some of the columns with fewer values by using statistical methods it can make easier later on to treat the missing values in other columns with a decision tree or some other predictive model.
#In any case we have quite a decent amount of missing data, Insulin has 374 missing values, which accounts for almost 48% percent of the whole data, that's a whole lot of missing data that we need to be careful when it comes to imputing.
#This can give us an idea of which variable have more weight over the response variable and when we do need to be more careful
pairs.panels(db1)

#"Missing"" Values Glucose column
#As I stated above the glucose values admits values of 0, given that it is of high risky to have a sugar level of between 0 and 7 it is indeed possible, and we are making a study about diabetes so having such values might be beneficial for us.
#And since we have seen that there are no outliers in that column I will restore the zeroes in that column
db1$Glucose[is.na(db1$Glucose)]<- 0
###Missing Values Blood Pressure column
#For this column we have 34 missing values which are not a lot and only accounts for almost 5% percent of the whole data

#As we can see both columns have a great deal of missing data, one almost reaching 50% of missing data (Insulin column) and another 30%, after I've tried to impute those values by a knn imputation and MICE (see unused codes at the end of the document) because of the small size of the data frame it didn't do any good because their predictions were to off to properly do something.
#The only choice leftis to either use the mean to impute new vlaues into those variables or by recommendation delete the columns and given the amount of missing data for those columns and the size of the data set I think I will be beter off without those column, mainly because imputing such amount of missing values with the mean might be a deterrent towards the models
cleandb2<-db1[1:3]
cleandb3<-db1[6:9]
cleandb<-cbind.data.frame(cleandb2,cleandb3)
#Althought my intention is to use caret package for my models and let caret handle automatically the data scaling and centering I will normalize the data set and save it with another name so I will test it in some of the models to see if doing it manually has a difference over the caret preProcessing function
cleandb1<-cleandb
normalize <- function(x) {
return ((x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x))) }
cleandb1 <- as.data.frame(lapply(cleandb1[1:7], normalize))
#Conclusion: The data indeed came with a lot of missing values that had to be identified, cleaned and imputed, but since the data frame was this small and the amount of missing data in some of the columns was that big, the best course of action was for those column to be removed of the whole data frame

STAGE FOUR - MODELLING

######Model Building
##Spliting Data set
#Althought it doesn't make much sense since I will be using K-fold cross validation due to the small size of the data frame it never hurts to split the data frame just in case

######Logistic Regression Model
#Another mistake that I made and thankfully it has been clarified is that with the amount of data given I need to perform K-fold cross validation, and for that I don't need to split the data set between training and validation because k-fold cross validation splits the data set itself by k-fold
#The first predictive model I will build will be a logistic regression model, since we are trying to predict a categorical variable I think it's an appropiate approach.
md1<-glm(Outcome ~., data=cleandb, family = "binomial")

RSS1 <- c(crossprod(md2$residuals))
MSE1 <- RSS1 / length(md2$residuals)
RMSE1 <- sqrt(MSE1)
RMSE1
[1] 3.860851
#RMSE for the second model (md3)

MSE2 <- RSS2 / length(md3$residuals)
RMSE2 <- sqrt(MSE2)
RMSE2
[1] 4.201256
#Interesting enough both models are similar but oddly enough the first model that contains a non significant variable performs better in terms on the RMSE than the second model
#The issue here as pointed out by Prof.Schedlbauer is that the data set is too small to make a partition good enough for the models to get enough data to be trained and tested, so the whole data set has to be used both for testing and training but to avoid overfitting a K-fold cross validation will be used, in this case a 10-fold cross validation using the Caret package and the model that has performed better above
ctrl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 10, savePredictions = TRUE)

                   ,  data=cleandb,trControl=ctrl, method="glm", family="binomial", preProcess= c("scale","center"))

rocplot <- function(pred, truth, ...) {
  predob = prediction(pred, truth)
  perf = performance(predob, "tpr", "fpr")
  plot(perf, ...)
  area <- auc(truth, pred)
  area <- format(round(area, 4), nsmall = 4)
  text(x=0.8, y=0.1, labels = paste("AUC =", area))
  # the reference x=y line
  segments(x0=0, y0=0, x1=1, y1=1, col="gray", lty=2)
}
#ROC for Logistic Regression

######KNN Model
#The next model I will be performing is KNN. There are a few things to mention before I get into the task.
#I will be using the caret package to perform the KNN algorithm, and this package has a few advantages , one is that allows me to imput a K value of my choice and it will run through all the K values and then pick the best performing k value. Another thing to mention is that caret also has a function to scale and center the data fed to the algorithm, hence why it might not be necessary to normalize the data, but since normalizing the data is part of the project I will test both models, one with caret taking care of the data and another with me normalizing the data before feeding it to the algorithm.
##First Knn run with caret treating the data
#This allows us to do 10-fold cross validation as our data set is too small to do a hold-out method
set.seed(60)
ctrl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 10, savePredictions = TRUE)
knn_model <- train(factor(Outcome)~ ., data = cleandb, method = "knn", trControl = ctrl, preProcess = c("center","scale"),tuneLength=50)
#here we are able to see how the caret package operates to chose the best K value, as it seems it changes over time, and that is because of the K-fold cross validation, set.seed should solve the issue (it does). ALso I have decides to imput the algorithm with a k-value bigger than sqrt(n) because ideally we want to try as many numbers as possible.

rocplot <- function(pred, truth, ...) {
  predob = prediction(pred, truth)
  perf = performance(predob, "tpr", "fpr")
  plot(perf, ...)
  area <- auc(truth, pred)
  area <- format(round(area, 4), nsmall = 4)
  text(x=0.8, y=0.1, labels = paste("AUC =", area))
  # the reference x=y line
  segments(x0=0, y0=0, x1=1, y1=1, col="gray", lty=2)
}

}

###### Naive Bayes Model

##MODEL ENSEMBLE
#The final step in this data mining/machine learning project will be to build a stacked model with the models proceses above, to see if the overall performance increases
library(caretEnsemble)
library("gbm")
library("caTools")
#I've seen this done a in a few examples but I didn't use it since I was not sure the purpose of it, now after running the ensemble model I udnerstand that it has to be performed in order for the function to work (caret will output an error "suggesting" you to use it)
cleandb_named<-cleandb
cleandb_named1<-cleandb1
cleandb_named$Outcome<-factor(make.names(cleandb$Outcome))
cleandb_named1$Outcome<-factor(make.names(cleandb_named1$Outcome))
#Here I train the trainControl method that it will be used to implement the algorithms in the caretList() function. I have created a resample for the Outcome column marked at 25 resamples.
trctrl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 10, repeats = 3,classProbs=TRUE,
                       index=createResample(cleandb_named$Outcome, 25),savePredictions = TRUE)
#This is the list of the models I will be using for the stack ensemble, the function careList will run them and train them before adding them altogether into the ensemble function
set.seed(65)
invisible(capture.output(
model_list1 <- caretList(Outcome ~ .,
  data=cleandb_named, trControl = trctrl,
  tuneList = list(
                 glm=caretModelSpec(method='glm', family='binomial'),
                 knn=caretModelSpec(method = "knn", preProcess = c("center","scale"),tuneLength=50),
                 rpart=caretModelSpec(method = "rpart",tuneLength = 10),
                 nnet=caretModelSpec(method="nnet",tuneLenght=10),
                 c50=caretModelSpec(method = "C5.0"),
                 naive=caretModelSpec(method = "nb")))))
#This allow me to see the correlation between models, and while the correlation is not very good, giving a try to the ensemble model doesn't hurt anyone                 
modelCor(resamples(model_list1))

set.seed(100)
#This creates a stacked caret ensemble model that will be used for pthe prediction of the outcome later on
invisible(capture.output(
stack.rf <- caretStack(model_list1, method="gbm", metric="Accuracy", trControl= trainControl(
                      method="boot",
    number=10,
    savePredictions=TRUE,
    classProbs=TRUE,
    summaryFunction=twoClassSummary))))
print(stack.rf)

#Conclusion: Quite odd that the model ensemble hasn't proved as useful as I first expected, more considering that it would counter the lack of data in this given data frame. Another issue with the model ensemble is that it clasifies quite a lot of cases false negative, and considering we are in the medical field that might be an issue.

#This is data imputation by KNN and MICE algorithm but due to the lack of enough data I have deciced to leave it as a part of the code but not run it with the rest of the chunks


sb1 <- na.omit(db1)
sb2<-sb1

#The first method of imputation will be by a KNN model and then a MICE decision tree
#I will impute some random missing values to the data so I can see how well this method performs with a working data set
set.seed(100)
sb1[sample(1:nrow(sb1), 30), "Insulin"] <- NA
sb1[sample(1:nrow(sb1), 30), "SkinThickness"] <- NA

library(DMwR)
knnOutput <- knnImputation(sb1[, !names(sb1) %in% "Outcome"], k=20)
anyNA(knnOutput)

actuals <- sb2$Insulin[is.na(sb1$Insulin)]
predicteds <- knnOutput[is.na(sb1$Insulin), "Insulin"]
regr.eval(actuals, predicteds)

actuals <- sb2$SkinThickness[is.na(sb1$SkinThickness)]
predicteds <- knnOutput[is.na(sb1$SkinThickness), "SkinThickness"]
regr.eval(actuals, predicteds)


library(mice)
miceMod <- mice(sb1[, !names(sb1) %in% "Outcome"], method="rf")  # perform mice imputation, based on random forests.
miceOutput <- complete(miceMod)  # generate the completed data.
anyNA(miceOutput)


actuals <- sb2$Insulin[is.na(sb1$Insulin)]
predicteds <- miceOutput[is.na(sb1$Insulin), "Insulin"]
regr.eval(actuals, predicteds)


actuals <- sb2$SkinThickness[is.na(sb1$SkinThickness)]
predicteds <- miceOutput[is.na(sb1$SkinThickness), "SkinThickness"]
mean(actuals != predicteds)

library(rpart)
class_mod <- rpart(Insulin ~ . - Outcome, data=sb1[!is.na(sb1$Insulin), ], method="anova", na.action=na.omit)  

anova_mod <- rpart(SkinThickness ~ . - Outcome, data=sb1[!is.na(sb1$SkinThickness), ], method="anova", na.action=na.omit)  
rad_pred <- predict(class_mod, sb1[is.na(sb1$Insulin), ])
ptratio_pred <- predict(anova_mod, sb1[is.na(sb1$SkinThickness), ])

actuals <- sb2$SkinThickness[is.na(sb1$SkinThickness)]
predicteds <- ptratio_pred
regr.eval(actuals, predicteds)

actuals <- sb2$Insulin[is.na(sb1$Insulin)]
predicteds <- ptratio_pred
mean(actuals != predicteds)


#Conclusion: It seems these method have performed rather bad given our data, I don't think it would be safe to impute the values with these methods as their predictions are not good enough. Because of this it seems there are only two methods left to deal with all this missing data. 1. Imputing the missing data with its mean, that after some research I have these ahs been a comon practice with this data set or 2. Deleting the columns with missing values and building the predictive models over that.

normalize <- function(x) {
return ((x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x))) }

######Ensemble Model Using Caret Package

#Although we have some decent accuracies, the best being the decision trees we sometimes can apply ensemble models to see if the accuracy can be improved over the original models. In here I will perform three different ways of model ensemble and see which one yields the best result and see if that's an improvement over the rest of the models

#The first model ensemble will be performe with the careEnsemble package and I will be running a what is called greedy ensemble, I will put them all together and see the improvement, if there is one.

#I've seen this done a in a few examples but I didn't use it since I was not sure the purpose of it, now after running the ensemble model I udnerstand that it has to be performed in order for the function to work (caret will output an error "suggesting" you to use it)
cleandb_named<-cleandb
cleandb_named1<-cleandb1
cleandb_named$Outcome<-factor(make.names(cleandb$Outcome))
cleandb_named1$Outcome<-factor(make.names(cleandb_named1$Outcome))

#set.seed(60)
library(caretEnsemble)
my_control <- trainControl(
  method="boot",
  number=10,
  savePredictions="final",
  classProbs=TRUE,
  index=createResample(cleandb_named1$Outcome, 25),
  summaryFunction=twoClassSummary
  )

model_list1 <- caretList(
  Outcome~., data=cleandb_named1,
  trControl=my_control,
  methodList=c("glm","knn","nnet", "rpart")
  )

#While the correlation for these models is not the best, as for these cases a lower correlations is better, is not terrible either so I will procceed to perform a greedy ensemble
modelCor(resamples(model_list1))

#Well this is good news, in here we already see a small improvement over the models I have performed before. The two models that have shown improvement is the glm and the ann, while the deicison tree has actually performed worse than by itself
greedy_ensemble <- caretEnsemble(
  model_list1, 
  metric="ROC",
  trControl=trainControl(
    number=10,
    summaryFunction=twoClassSummary,
    classProbs=TRUE
    ))
summary(greedy_ensemble)


library("caTools")
ensemble1_pred <- lapply(model_list1, predict, newdata=cleandb_named1, type="prob")
ensemble1_pred <- lapply(ensemble1_pred, function(x) x[,"X1"])
ensemble1_pred  <- data.frame(ensemble1_pred)
ens_preds <- predict(greedy_ensemble, newdata=cleandb_named1, type="prob")
ensemble1_pred$ensemble <- ens_preds

#Interestingly enough it seems that KNN performs better than the ensemble model, also ANN as performed better too, while the decision tree has performed worse. This might by cause by the correlation between the different models.
#I will try to do different runs while substracting some models and see if it improves or not
colAUC(ensemble1_pred, cleandb_named1$Outcome)

pred.logit <- rep("X1",length(ensemble1_pred$ensemble))
pred.logit[ensemble1_pred$ensemble>=0.5] <- "X0"
confusionMatrix(cleandb_named$Outcome, pred.logit)


#conclusion: Unfortunately and not what I expected the ensemble model performs worse than their models, I've noticed that the KNN algorithm outputs a high AUC value making it the best model within the ensemble. The only moment where the ensemble model is better is by using the ANN and the decision tree, which interesting enough those two models have performe rather well in theri first runs above

######Stacked Ensemble Model Using Caret Package

#Now the second ensemble model I will be using is an stacked ensemble model, what this does is make a collection of all the predictive models so it should imrpvoe over the singel models
glm_ensemble <- caretStack(
  model_list1,
  method="rpart",
  metric="ROC",
  trControl=trainControl(
    method="boot",
    number=10,
    savePredictions="final",
    classProbs=TRUE,
    summaryFunction=twoClassSummary
  )
)


model_preds2 <- ensemble1_pred
model_preds2$ensemble <- predict(glm_ensemble, newdata=cleandb_named, type="prob")
CF <- coef(glm_ensemble$ens_model$finalModel)[-1]
colAUC(model_preds2, cleandb_named$Outcome)

#Again this stacked ensemble model doesn't perform better than their individual aprts, and for some odd reason that I haven't been able to figure out KNN yields by far better results than any other model

######Stacked Ensemble Model Using Caret Package and GBM (Gradient Boosting)

#Now this next ensemble model I am using a GRadient Boosting to see if we can build a stronger ensemble model that outperforms the rest of the other models.

library("gbm")
gbm_ensemble <- caretStack(
  model_list1,
  method="gbm",
  verbose=FALSE,
  tuneLength=10,
  metric="ROC",
  trControl=trainControl(
    method="boot",
    number=10,
    savePredictions="final",
    classProbs=TRUE,
    summaryFunction=twoClassSummary
  )
)
print(gbm_ensemble)
model_preds3 <-ensemble1_pred
model_preds3$ensemble <- predict(gbm_ensemble, newdata=cleandb_named1, type="prob")
colAUC(model_preds3, cleandb_named1$Outcome)

#And again, not even this ensemble model performs better than any of the other models

#Conclusion: It is indeed odd that the ensemble models do not outperform the rest of the models, and for some reason even after some time tinkering with the algorithms I haven't been able to figure it out, although in favour of this result I must say it's not the oddest (I had to look up this word, but apparently is correct) result I've seen this semester. For now and after multiple tries to find the root and cause of this, I have decided that maybe this given data is not ideal to make a stacked model, or the small amount of data present doesn't allow to make a good ensemble model, although that doesn't seem to be very logical since one would think that using ensemble model could be a solution for small datasets
